# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: yara-rules
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Antivirus software was originally developed to detect and remove computer viruses, hence the name.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] However, with the proliferation of other malware, antivirus software started to protect against other computer threats.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Some products also include protection from malicious URLs, spam, and phishing.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] The first known computer virus appeared in 1971 and was dubbed the "Creeper virus".
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] This computer virus infected Digital Equipment Corporation's (DEC) PDP-10 mainframe computers running the TENEX operating system.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] The Creeper virus was eventually deleted by a program created by Ray Tomlinson and known as "The Reaper".
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Some people consider "The Reaper" the first antivirus software ever written – it may be the case, but the Reaper was actually a virus itself specifically designed to remove the Creeper virus.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] The Creeper virus was followed by several other viruses.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] The first known that appeared "in the wild" was "Elk Cloner", in 1981, which infected Apple II computers.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 1983, the term *"computer virus"* was coined by Fred Cohen in one of the first ever published academic papers on computer viruses.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] The first IBM PC compatible "in the wild" computer virus, and one of the first real widespread infections, was "Brain" in 1986.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] From then, the number of viruses has grown exponentially.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Most of the computer viruses written in the early and mid-1980s were limited to self-reproduction and had no specific damage routine built into the code.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] That changed when more and more programmers became acquainted with computer virus programming and created viruses that manipulated or even destroyed data on infected computers.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Before internet connectivity was widespread, computer viruses were typically spread by infected floppy disks.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Antivirus software came into use, but was updated relatively infrequently.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] During this time, virus checkers essentially had to check executable files and the boot sectors of floppy disks and hard disks.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] However, as internet usage became common, viruses began to spread online.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] There are competing claims for the innovator of the first antivirus product.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Possibly, the first publicly documented removal of an "in the wild" computer virus (the "Vienna virus") was performed by Bernd Fix in 1987.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 1985, in United Kingdom, Jan Hruska and Peter Lammer founded the security firm Sophos and began producing their first antivirus and encryption products.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In the same period, in Hungary, VirusBuster was founded (and subsequently incorporated by Sophos).
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 1987, Andreas Lüning and Kai Figge, who founded G Data Software in 1985, released their first antivirus product for the Atari ST platform.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 1987, the *Ultimate Virus Killer (UVK)* was also released.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] This was the de facto industry standard virus killer for the Atari ST and Atari Falcon, the last version of which (version 9.0) was released in April 2004.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 1987, in the United States, John McAfee founded the McAfee company and, at the end of that year, he released the first version of VirusScan.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Also in 1987 (in Czechoslovakia), Peter Paško, Rudolf Hrubý, and Miroslav Trnka created the first version of NOD antivirus.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 1987, Fred Cohen wrote that *there is no algorithm that can perfectly detect all possible computer viruses*.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Finally, at the end of 1987, the first two heuristic antivirus utilities were released: *Flushot Plus* by Ross Greenberg and *Anti4us* by Erwin Lanting.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] However, the kind of heuristic used by early AV engines was totally different from those used today.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] The first product with a heuristic engine resembling modern ones was F-PROT in 1991.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Early heuristic engines were based on dividing the binary into different sections: data section, code section (in a legitimate binary, it usually starts always from the same location).
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Indeed, the initial viruses re-organized the layout of the sections, or overrode the initial portion of a section in order to jump to the very end of the file where malicious code was located—only going back to resume execution of the original code.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] This was a very specific pattern, not used at the time by any legitimate software, which represented an elegant heuristic to catch suspicious code.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Other kinds of more advanced heuristics were later added, such as suspicious section names, incorrect header size, regular expressions, and partial pattern in-memory matching.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 1988, the growth of antivirus companies continued.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In Germany, Tjark Auerbach founded Avira (*H+BEDV* at the time) and released the first version of *AntiVir* (named *"Luke Filewalker"* at the time).
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In Spain, Carlos Jiménez released the first version of his antivirus (he founded Anyware Seguridad Informática, now part of McAfee, one year later).
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In Bulgaria, Vesselin Bontchev released his first freeware antivirus program (he later joined FRISK Software).
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Also Frans Veldman released the first version of ThunderByte Antivirus, also known as *TBAV* (he sold his company to Norman Safeground in 1998).
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In Czechoslovakia, Pavel Baudiš and Eduard Kučera founded Avast Software (at the time *ALWIL Software*) and released their first version of avast! antivirus.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In June 1988, in South Korea, Ahn Cheol-Soo released its first antivirus software, called *V1* (he founded AhnLab later in 1995).
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Finally, in autumn 1988, in the United Kingdom, Alan Solomon founded S&S International and created his *Dr.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Solomon's Anti-Virus Toolkit* (although he launched it commercially only in 1991 – in 1998 Solomon's company was acquired by McAfee, then known as Network Associates Inc.).
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Also in 1988, a mailing list named VIRUS-L was started on the BITNET/EARN network where new viruses and the possibilities of detecting and eliminating viruses were discussed.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Some members of this mailing list were: Alan Solomon, Eugene Kaspersky (Kaspersky Lab), Friðrik Skúlason (FRISK Software), John McAfee (McAfee), Luis Corrons (Panda Security), Mikko Hyppönen (F-Secure), Péter Szőr, Tjark Auerbach (Avira) and Vesselin Bontchev (FRISK Software).
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 1989, in Iceland, Friðrik Skúlason created the first version of F-PROT Anti-Virus (he founded FRISK Software only in 1993).
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Meanwhile, in the United States, Symantec (founded by Gary Hendrix in 1982) launched its first *Symantec antivirus for Macintosh* (SAM).
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] SAM 2.0, released March 1990, incorporated technology allowing users to easily update SAM to intercept and eliminate new viruses, including many that didn't exist at the time of the program's release.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 1990, in Spain, Mikel Urizarbarrena founded Panda Security (*Panda Software* at the time).
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In Hungary, the security researcher Péter Szőr released the first version of *Pasteur* antivirus.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 1990, the Computer Antivirus Research Organization (CARO) was founded.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 1991, CARO released the *"Virus Naming Scheme"*, originally written by Friðrik Skúlason and Vesselin Bontchev.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Although this naming scheme is now outdated, it remains the only existing standard that most computer security companies and researchers ever attempted to adopt.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] CARO members includes: Alan Solomon, Costin Raiu, Dmitry Gryaznov, Eugene Kaspersky, Friðrik Skúlason, Igor Muttik, Mikko Hyppönen, Morton Swimmer, Nick FitzGerald, Padgett Peterson, Peter Ferrie, Righard Zwienenberg and Vesselin Bontchev.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 1991, in the United States, Symantec released the first version of Norton AntiVirus.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] On the other hand, in Finland, F-Secure (founded in 1988 by Petri Allas and Risto Siilasmaa – with the name of Data Fellows) released the first version of their antivirus product.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] F-Secure claims to be the first antivirus firm to establish a presence on the World Wide Web.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 1991, the European Institute for Computer Antivirus Research (EICAR) was founded to further antivirus research and improve development of antivirus software.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 1992, in Russia, Igor Danilov released the first version of *SpiderWeb*, which later became Dr.Web.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 1994, AV-TEST reported that there were 28,613 unique malware samples (based on MD5) in their database.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 1996, in Romania, Bitdefender was founded and released the first version of *Anti-Virus eXpert* (AVX).
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 1997, in Russia, Eugene Kaspersky and Natalya Kaspersky co-founded security firm Kaspersky Lab.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 1996, there was also the first "in the wild" Linux virus, known as *"Staog"*.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 1999, AV-TEST reported that there were 98,428 unique malware samples (based on MD5) in their database.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 2000, Rainer Link and Howard Fuhs started the first open source antivirus engine, called *OpenAntivirus Project*.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 2001, Tomasz Kojm released the first version of ClamAV, the first ever open source antivirus engine to be commercialised.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 2007, ClamAV was bought by Sourcefire, which in turn was acquired by Cisco Systems in 2013.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 2002, in United Kingdom, Morten Lund and Theis Søndergaard co-founded the antivirus firm BullGuard.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 2005, AV-TEST reported that there were 333,425 unique malware samples (based on MD5) in their database.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 2007, AV-TEST reported a number of 5,490,960 new unique malware samples (based on MD5) only for that year.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 2012 and 2013, antivirus firms reported a new malware samples range from 300,000 to over 500,000 per day.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 2005, F-Secure was the first security firm that developed an Anti-Rootkit technology, called *BlackLight*.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Because most users are usually connected to the Internet on a continual basis, Jon Oberheide first proposed a Cloud-based antivirus design in 2008.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In February 2008 McAfee Labs added the industry-first cloud-based anti-malware functionality to VirusScan under the name Artemis.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] It was tested by AV-Comparatives in February 2008 and officially unveiled in August 2008 in McAfee VirusScan.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Cloud AV created problems for comparative testing of security software – part of the AV definitions was out of testers control (on constantly updated AV company servers) thus making results non-repeatable.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] As a result, Anti-Malware Testing Standards Organisation (AMTSO) started working on method of testing cloud products which was adopted on May 7, 2009.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 2011, AVG introduced a similar cloud service, called Protective Cloud Technology.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Following the 2013 release of the APT 1 report from Mandiant, the industry has seen a shift towards signature-less approaches to the problem capable of detecting and mitigating zero-day attacks.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Numerous approaches to address these new forms of threats have appeared, including behavioral detection, artificial intelligence, machine learning, and cloud-based file detection.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] According to Gartner, it is expected the rise of new entrants, such Carbon Black, Cylance and Crowdstrike will force end point protection incumbents into a new phase of innovation and acquisition.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] One method from Bromium involves micro-virtualization to protect desktops from malicious code execution initiated by the end user.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Another approach from SentinelOne and Carbon Black focuses on behavioral detection by building a full context around every process execution path in real time, while Cylance leverages an artificial intelligence model based on machine learning.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Increasingly, these signature-less approaches have been defined by the media and analyst firms as "next-generation" antivirus and are seeing rapid market adoption as certified antivirus replacement technologies by firms such as Coalfire and DirectDefense.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In response, traditional antivirus vendors such as Trend Micro, Symantec and Sophos have responded by incorporating "next-gen" offerings into their portfolios as analyst firms such as Forrester and Gartner have called traditional signature-based antivirus "ineffective" and "outdated".
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] As of Windows 8, Windows includes its own free antivirus protection under the Windows Defender brand.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Despite bad detection scores in its early days, AV-Test now certifies Defender as one of its top products.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] While it isn't publicly known how the inclusion of antivirus software in Windows affected antivirus sales, Google search traffic for antivirus has declined significantly since 2010.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Since 2016, there has been a notable amount of consolidation in the industry.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Avast purchased AVG in 2016 for $1.3 billion.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Avira was acquired by Norton owner Gen Digital (then NortonLifeLock) in 2020 for $360 million.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 2021, the Avira division of Gen Digital acquired BullGuard.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] The BullGuard brand was discontinued in 2022 and its customers were migrated to Norton.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 2022, Gen Digital acquired Avast, effectively consolidating four major antivirus brands under one owner.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In September 2024, following the US Commerce Department's ban on Kaspersky, Pango Group acquired its customers (about 1 million).
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] The customers received continued services with no action required on their part.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Then, in December 2024, Pango Group merged with Total Security, the provider of Total AV antivirus.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] The combined entity, now called Point Wild, has an enterprise value of $1.7 billion.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] As of 2024, more than half of Americans use built-in antivirus protection for their devices like Microsoft Defender or XProtect from Apple.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] However, about 121 million adults still use third-party antivirus software.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Half of these adults use paid products, and about 50% of third-party software users - the owners of personal computers and Windows operating systems.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Antivirus programs on mobile devices are used by 17% of adults.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] The 2025 antivirus market report confirms that most third-party antivirus users are on desktop devices, primarily aged between 35 and 45.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In contrast, younger users (18–25) tend to rely on ad blockers instead.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In the U.S., on average, 75–85% of people use antivirus software or some other form of protection on at least one device.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Antivirus software for computers and mobile devices is predominantly used by residents of large cities.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Mobile device users more often rely on password managers rather than antivirus software for digital security.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Moreover, the majority of password‑manager users live in medium‑sized and small towns.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Cohen demonstrated that the algorithm which would be able to detect all possible viruses can't possibly exist (like the algorithm which determines whether or not the given program halts).
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] However, using different layers of defense, a good detection rate may be achieved.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Traditional antivirus software relies heavily upon signatures to identify malware.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Substantially, when a malware sample arrives in the hands of an antivirus firm, it is analysed by malware researchers or by dynamic analysis systems.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Then, once it is determined to be a malware, a proper signature of the file is extracted and added to the signatures database of the antivirus software.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Many viruses start as a single infection and through either mutation or refinements by other attackers, can grow into dozens of slightly different strains, called variants.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Generic detection refers to the detection and removal of multiple threats using a single virus definition.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] For example, the Vundo trojan has several family members, depending on the antivirus vendor's classification.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Symantec classifies members of the Vundo family into two distinct categories, *Trojan.Vundo* and *Trojan.Vundo.B*.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] While it may be advantageous to identify a specific virus, it can be quicker to detect a virus family through a generic signature or through an inexact match to an existing signature.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Virus researchers find common areas that all viruses in a family share uniquely and can thus create a single generic signature.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] These signatures often contain non-contiguous code, using wildcard characters where differences lie.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] These wildcards allow the scanner to detect viruses even if they are padded with extra, meaningless code.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] A detection that uses this method is said to be "heuristic detection".
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Anti-virus software can attempt to scan for rootkits.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] A rootkit is a type of malware designed to gain administrative-level control over a computer system without being detected.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Rootkits can change how the operating system functions and in some cases can tamper with the anti-virus program and render it ineffective.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Rootkits are also difficult to remove, in some cases requiring a complete re-installation of the operating system.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Real-time protection, on-access scanning, background guard, resident shield, autoprotect, and other synonyms refer to the automatic protection provided by most antivirus, anti-spyware, and other anti-malware programs.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] This monitors computer systems for suspicious activity such as computer viruses, spyware, adware, and other malicious objects.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Real-time protection detects threats in opened files and scans apps in real-time as they are installed on the device.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] When inserting a CD, opening an email, or browsing the web, or when a file already on the computer is opened or executed.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Machine learning has emerged as a core detection method in modern antivirus software, using algorithms trained on large datasets to classify software as malicious or benign.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] ML-based approaches are diverse, but detectors typically extract features from files, such as API call sequences, byte n-grams, opcode distributions, behavioral characteristics, or even raw bytes, and train classifiers to identify malware based on learned patterns from this data.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] ML-based detection can be highly effective, but still faces significant challenges.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Concept drift occurs as malware continuously evolves, causing trained models to degrade in accuracy over time without regular retraining on fresh samples.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Research has demonstrated that even simple obfuscation techniques can create adversarial variants that bypass ML-based detectors while preserving malicious functionality.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Additionally, the highly imbalanced nature of real-world data, where benign files vastly outnumber malicious ones, makes acquiring training data difficult and requires careful tuning to avoid unacceptable false positive rates.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Some commercial antivirus software end-user license agreements include a clause that the subscription will be automatically renewed, and the purchaser's credit card automatically billed, at the renewal time without explicit approval.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] For example, McAfee requires users to unsubscribe at least 60 days before the expiration of the present subscription, while Bitdefender sends notifications to unsubscribe 30 days before the renewal.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Norton AntiVirus also renews subscriptions automatically by default.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Some apparent antivirus programs are actually malware masquerading as legitimate software, such as WinFixer, MS Antivirus, and Mac Defender.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] A "false positive" or "false alarm" is when antivirus software identifies a non-malicious file as malware.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] When this happens, it can cause serious problems.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] For example, if an antivirus program is configured to immediately delete or quarantine infected files, as is common on Microsoft Windows antivirus applications, a false positive in an essential file can render the Windows operating system or some applications unusable.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Recovering from such damage to critical software infrastructure incurs technical support costs and businesses can be forced to close whilst remedial action is undertaken.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Running (the real-time protection of) multiple antivirus programs concurrently can degrade performance and create conflicts.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] However, using a concept called multiscanning, several companies (including G Data Software and Microsoft) have created applications which can run multiple engines concurrently.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] It is sometimes necessary to temporarily disable virus protection when installing major updates such as Windows Service Packs or updating graphics card drivers.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Active antivirus protection may partially or completely prevent the installation of a major update.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Anti-virus software can cause problems during the installation of an operating system upgrade, e.g. when upgrading to a newer version of Windows "in place"—without erasing the previous version of Windows.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Microsoft recommends that anti-virus software be disabled to avoid conflicts with the upgrade installation process.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Active anti-virus software can also interfere with a firmware update process.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] The functionality of a few computer programs can be hampered by active anti-virus software.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] For example, TrueCrypt, a disk encryption program, states on its troubleshooting page that anti-virus programs can conflict with TrueCrypt and cause it to malfunction or operate very slowly.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Anti-virus software can impair the performance and stability of games running in the Steam platform.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Support issues also exist around antivirus application interoperability with common solutions like SSL VPN remote access and network access control products.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] These technology solutions often have policy assessment applications that require an up-to-date antivirus to be installed and running.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] If the antivirus application is not recognized by the policy assessment, whether because the antivirus application has been updated or because it is not part of the policy assessment library, the user will be unable to connect.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Studies in December 2007 showed that the effectiveness of antivirus software had decreased in the previous year, particularly against unknown or zero day attacks.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] The computer magazine *c't* found that detection rates for these threats had dropped from 40 to 50% in 2006 to 20–30% in 2007.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] At that time, the only exception was the NOD32 antivirus, which managed a detection rate of 68%.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] According to the *ZeuS tracker* website the average detection rate for all variants of the ZeuS trojan is as low as 40%.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] The problem is magnified by the changing intent of virus authors.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Some years ago it was obvious when a virus infection was present.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] At the time, viruses were written by amateurs and exhibited destructive behavior or pop-ups.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Modern viruses are often written by professionals, financed by criminal organizations.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 2008, Eva Chen, CEO of Trend Micro, stated that the anti-virus industry has over-hyped how effective its products are—and so has been misleading customers—for years.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Independent testing on all the major virus scanners consistently shows that none provides 100% virus detection.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] The best ones provided as high as 99.9% detection for simulated real-world situations, while the lowest provided 91.1% in tests conducted in August 2013.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Many virus scanners produce false positive results as well, identifying benign files as malware.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Although methods may differ, some notable independent quality testing agencies include AV-Comparatives, ICSA Labs, SE Labs, West Coast Labs, *Virus Bulletin*, AV-TEST and other members of the Anti-Malware Testing Standards Organization.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Anti-virus programs are not always effective against new viruses, even those that use non-signature-based methods that should detect new viruses.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] The reason for this is that the virus designers test their new viruses on the major anti-virus applications to make sure that they are not detected before releasing them into the wild.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Some new viruses, particularly ransomware, use polymorphic code to avoid detection by virus scanners.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] A proof of concept virus has used the Graphics Processing Unit (GPU) to avoid detection from anti-virus software.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] The potential success of this involves bypassing the CPU in order to make it much harder for security researchers to analyse the inner workings of such malware.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Detecting rootkits is a major challenge for anti-virus programs.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Rootkits have full administrative access to the computer and are invisible to users and hidden from the list of running processes in the task manager.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Rootkits can modify the inner workings of the operating system and tamper with antivirus programs.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] If a file has been infected by a computer virus, anti-virus software will attempt to remove the virus code from the file during disinfection, but it is not always able to restore the file to its undamaged state.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In such circumstances, damaged files can only be restored from existing backups or shadow copies (this is also true for ransomware); installed software that is damaged requires re-installation (however, see System File Checker).
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Any writeable firmware in the computer can be infected by malicious code.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] This is a major concern, as an infected BIOS could require the actual BIOS chip to be replaced to ensure the malicious code is completely removed.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Anti-virus software is not effective at protecting firmware and the motherboard BIOS from infection.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] In 2014, security researchers discovered that USB devices contain writeable firmware which can be modified with malicious code (dubbed "BadUSB"), which anti-virus software cannot detect or prevent.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] The malicious code can run undetected on the computer and could even infect the operating system prior to it booting up.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Antivirus software has some drawbacks, first of which that it can impact a computer's performance.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Furthermore, inexperienced users can be lulled into a false sense of security when using the computer, considering their computers to be invulnerable, and may have problems understanding the prompts and decisions that antivirus software presents them with.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] An incorrect decision may lead to a security breach.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] If the antivirus software employs heuristic detection, it must be fine-tuned to minimize misidentifying harmless software as malicious (false positive).
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Antivirus software itself usually runs at the highly trusted kernel level of the operating system to allow it access to all the potential malicious process and files, creating a potential avenue of attack.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] The US National Security Agency (NSA) and the UK Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ) intelligence agencies, respectively, have been exploiting anti-virus software to spy on users.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Anti-virus software has highly privileged and trusted access to the underlying operating system, which makes it a much more appealing target for remote attacks.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Additionally anti-virus software is "years behind security-conscious client-side applications like browsers or document readers.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] It means that Acrobat Reader, Microsoft Word or Google Chrome are harder to exploit than 90 percent of the anti-virus products out there", according to Joxean Koret, a researcher with Coseinc, a Singapore-based information security consultancy.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Antivirus software running on individual computers is the most common method employed of guarding against malware, but it is not the only solution.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Other solutions can also be employed by users, including Unified Threat Management (UTM), hardware and network firewalls, Cloud-based antivirus, online scanners, and Content Disarm & Reconstruction (CDR).
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Network firewalls prevent unknown programs and processes from accessing the system.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] However, they are not antivirus systems and make no attempt to identify or remove anything.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] They may protect against infection from outside the protected computer or network, and limit the activity of any malicious software which is present by blocking incoming or outgoing requests on certain TCP/IP ports.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] A firewall is designed to deal with broader system threats that come from network connections into the system and is not an alternative to a virus protection system.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Cloud antivirus is a technology that uses lightweight agent software on the protected computer, while offloading the majority of data analysis to the provider's infrastructure.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] One approach to implementing cloud antivirus involves scanning suspicious files using multiple antivirus engines.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] This approach was proposed by an early implementation of the cloud antivirus concept called CloudAV.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] CloudAV was designed to send programs or documents to a network cloud where multiple antivirus and behavioral detection programs are used simultaneously in order to improve detection rates.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Parallel scanning of files using potentially incompatible antivirus scanners is achieved by spawning a virtual machine per detection engine and therefore eliminating any possible issues.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] CloudAV can also perform "retrospective detection", whereby the cloud detection engine rescans all files in its file access history when a new threat is identified thus improving new threat detection speed.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Finally, CloudAV is a solution for effective virus scanning on devices that lack the computing power to perform the scans themselves.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Some examples of cloud anti-virus products are Panda Cloud Antivirus and Immunet.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Comodo Group has also produced cloud-based anti-virus.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Some antivirus vendors maintain websites with free online scanning capability of the entire computer, critical areas only, local disks, folders or files.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Periodic online scanning is a good idea for those that run antivirus applications on their computers because those applications are frequently slow to catch threats.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] One of the first things that malicious software does in an attack is disable any existing antivirus software and sometimes the only way to know of an attack is by turning to an online resource that is not installed on the infected computer.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Content Disarm & Reconstruction (CDR) technology protects a network from malware by removing components from inbound files which do not rigorously conform with the standards of that file type.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] It does so by rebuilding the original files without any illegitimate components present.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Part of the CDR process may also involve flattening and converting the reconstructed files to Portable Document Format (PDF) for maximum safety.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] CDR malware removal does not attempt to identify malware behavior before taking action; rather, it employs a zero-trust approach against files entering a network perimeter.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] This can make it an effective solution for protecting networks against zero-day vulnerabilities.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Virus removal tools are available to help remove stubborn infections or a certain type of infection.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Examples include *Windows Malicious Software Removal Tool*, *Kaspersky Virus Removal Tool*, and *Sophos Scan & Clean*.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] It is also worth noting that sometimes antivirus software can produce a false-positive result, indicating an infection where there is none.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] A rescue disk that is bootable, such as a CD or USB storage device, can be used to run antivirus software outside of the installed operating system in order to remove infections while they are dormant.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] A bootable rescue disk can be useful when, for example, the installed operating system is no longer bootable or has malware that is resisting all attempts to be removed by the installed antivirus software.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] Examples of software that can be used on a bootable rescue disk include the *Kaspersky Rescue Disk*, *Trend Micro Rescue Disk*, and *Comodo Rescue Disk*.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] According to an FBI survey, major businesses lose $12 million annually dealing with virus incidents.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] A survey by Symantec in 2009 found that a third of small to medium-sized business did not use antivirus protection at that time, whereas more than 80% of home users had some kind of antivirus installed.
[src:yara-rules/antivirus-software] According to a sociological survey conducted by G Data Software in 2010 49% of women did not use any antivirus program at all.
[src:yara-rules/malware-analysis] Standardized evaluation of sandbox-based analysis products has also emerged.
[src:yara-rules/malware-analysis] In 2025, the Anti-Malware Testing Standards Organization (AMTSO) introduced the first *Sandbox Evaluation Framework*, aimed at providing consistent, use-case-driven testing criteria for sandbox malware analysis tools.
[src:yara-rules/malware-analysis] The use of artificial intelligence (AI) in malware detection has been an active area of research within the field of cybersecurity.
[src:yara-rules/malware-analysis] One study compared the behavior of AI against human behavior to understand the similarities and differences in how these two parties performed.
[src:yara-rules/malware-analysis] Antivirus softwares have used these studies to come to a conclusion that a combination of both practices would be most ideal.
[src:yara-rules/malware-analysis] Since AI can use static analysis at a much faster rate than humans in malware detection, the antivirus software will send the samples to the AI for an initial screening.
[src:yara-rules/malware-analysis] If the sample is more complex and the AI cannot make a definitive conclusion, then the sample will be sent to a human to observe the sample in more detail.
[src:yara-rules/malware-analysis] In this way, more samples can be correctly identified as malware or benign.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] In computer science, **pattern matching** is the act of checking a given sequence of tokens for the presence of the constituents of some pattern.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] In contrast to pattern recognition, the match usually must be exact: "either it will or will not be a match." The patterns generally have the form of either sequences or tree structures.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Uses of pattern matching include outputting the locations (if any) of a pattern within a token sequence, to output some component of the matched pattern, and to substitute the matching pattern with some other token sequence (i.e., search and replace).
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Sequence patterns (e.g., a text string) are often described using regular expressions and matched using techniques such as backtracking.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Tree patterns are used in some programming languages as a general tool to process data based on its structure, e.g.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] C#, F#, Haskell, Java, ML, Python, Racket, Ruby, Rust, Scala, Swift and the symbolic mathematics language Mathematica have special syntax for expressing tree patterns and a language construct for conditional execution and value retrieval based on it.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Often it is possible to give alternative patterns that are tried one by one, which yields a powerful conditional programming construct.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Pattern matching sometimes includes support for guards.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Early programming languages with pattern matching constructs include COMIT (1957), SNOBOL (1962), which introduced pattern matching as a core, first-class language capability for string and text manipulation.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] This paradigm evolved into structured, tree-based data evaluation with Refal (1968), which used pattern matching to manipulate symbolic expressions.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] The concept was soon adapted into logic programming with Prolog (1972), where pattern matching took the form of structural unification to resolve logical queries.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Functional programming languages rapidly adopted and formalized the feature across the late 1970s and early 1980s, beginning with the St Andrews Static Language (SASL) (1976), NPL (1977), and the Kent Recursive Calculator (KRC) (1981).
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] The pattern matching feature of function arguments in the language ML (1973) and its dialect Standard ML (1983) heavily formalized compile-time exhaustiveness checking.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] This approach has been carried over to some other functional programming languages that were influenced by them, such as Haskell (1990), Scala (2004), and F# (2005).
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] The pattern matching construct with the `match` keyword that was introduced in the ML dialect Caml (1985) was followed by languages such as OCaml (1996), F# (2005), F* (2011), and Rust (2015).
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Over time, multi-paradigm languages begin implementing algebraic data types and pattern matching natively, culminating in modern implementations like Python's `match-case` syntax (2021) and Java's pattern matching enhancements (2023).
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Many text editors support pattern matching of various kinds to facilitate advanced search-and-replace capabilities.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] The QED editor, designed by Ken Thompson, was a pioneer in supporting regular expression searching.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Thompson's implementation of regular expression parsing in QED laid the groundwork for the text search utilities in ed, sed, and grep.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Furthermore, some versions of the TECO editor supported advanced matching features, including the logical OR operator in searches.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Computer algebra systems (CAS) generally support pattern matching on algebraic expressions to achieve symbolic simplification and integration.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Early systems like Macsyma (1968) used semantic pattern matching to recognize algebraic equivalence; for example, its internal engine could successfully match both `3x2 + 4` and `(x + 1)(x + 6)` as occurrences of a "quadratic in x" pattern template.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Modern computer algebra systems, including Mathematica and Maple, rely heavily on pattern-matching rules to transform user expressions, find analytical solutions to differential equations, and build user-defined simplification frameworks.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Pattern matching involves specialized terminology.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Pattern languages can be rich; see below for terminology denoting specific kinds of pattern.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] The value to be examined and matched against a pattern.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Replacement of a portion of a scrutinee data structure with some computed value.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] The computation may depend on the replaced portion of the scrutinee as well as on other bindings extracted from the scrutinee.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] While some concepts are relatively common to many pattern languages, other pattern languages include unique or unusual extensions.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] that portion when the continuation executes.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] , the wildcard pattern accepts all values without examining them further, ignoring their structure.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] is an expression that must succeed (or yield Boolean true) as a final step before considering a pattern to have successfully matched.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] ), guards are written using a restricted subset of the full language; in others (e.g.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] The predicate is applied to the portion of the scrutinee corresponding to the position of the predicate in the pattern; if the predicate responds with Boolean false, the pattern is considered to have failed.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] to each element; the overall pattern thus succeeds only when the scrutinee is a list of even numbers.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] , where a user-defined function transforms the portion of the scrutinee corresponding to the position of the view pattern before continuing the match.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] View patterns generalize predicate patterns, allowing further matching on the result of the function rather than simply expecting a Boolean value.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Some pattern languages allow direct comparison of portions of the scrutinee with previously-computed (or constant) data structures.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] In Erlang, mention of any variable already in scope in a pattern causes it to act as a constraint in this way (instead of as a binding).
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Some languages allow macros in pattern context to allow abstraction over patterns.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] The simplest pattern in pattern matching is an explicit value or a variable.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Now, whenever f is given 0 as argument the pattern matches and the function returns 1.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] With any other argument, the matching and thus the function fail.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Here, the first `n` is a single variable pattern, which will match absolutely any argument and bind it to name n to be used in the rest of the definition.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] In Haskell (unlike at least Hope), patterns are tried in order so the first definition still applies in the very specific case of the input being 0, while for any other argument the function returns `n * f (n-1)` with n being the argument.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] The wildcard pattern (often written as `_`) is also simple: like a variable name, it matches any value, but does not bind the value to any name.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Algorithms for matching wildcards in simple string-matching situations have been developed in a number of recursive and non-recursive varieties.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] More complex patterns can be built from the primitive ones of the previous section, usually in the same way as values are built by combining other values.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] The difference then is that with variable and wildcard parts, a pattern does not build into a single value, but matches a group of values that are the combination of the concrete elements and the elements that are allowed to vary within the structure of the pattern.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] A tree pattern describes a part of a tree by starting with a node and specifying some branches and nodes and leaving some unspecified with a variable or wildcard pattern.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] It may help to think of the abstract syntax tree of a programming language and algebraic data types.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] In Haskell, the following line defines an algebraic data type `Color` that has a single data constructor `ColorConstructor` that wraps an integer and a string.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] The constructor is a node in a tree and the integer and string are leaves in branches.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] When we want to write functions to make `Color` an abstract data type, we wish to write functions to interface with the data type, and thus we want to extract some data from the data type, for example, just the string or just the integer part of `Color`.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] If we pass a variable that is of type Color, how can we get the data out of this variable?
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] The creations of these functions can be automated by Haskell's data record syntax.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] This OCaml example which defines a red–black tree and a function to re-balance it after element insertion shows how to match on a more complex structure generated by a recursive data type.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] The compiler verifies at compile-time that the list of cases is exhaustive and none are redundant.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Pattern matching can be used to filter data of a certain structure.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] In Mathematica, the only structure that exists is the tree, which is populated by symbols.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] In the traditional, more suitable syntax, the symbols are written as they are and the levels of the tree are represented using `[]`, so that for instance `a[b,c]` is a tree with a as the parent, and b and c as the children.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] A pattern in Mathematica involves putting "_" at positions in that tree.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] will match elements such as A[1], A[2], or more generally A[*x*] where *x* is any entity.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] In this case, `A` is the concrete element, while `_` denotes the piece of tree that can be varied.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] A symbol prepended to `_` binds the match to that variable name while a symbol appended to `_` restricts the matches to nodes of that symbol.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Note that even blanks themselves are internally represented as `Blank[]` for `_` and `Blank[x]` for `_x`.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Pattern matching applies to the *structure* of expressions.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] because only these elements will match the pattern `a[b[_],_]` above.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] In Mathematica, it is also possible to extract structures as they are created in the course of computation, regardless of how or where they appear.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] The function `Trace` can be used to monitor a computation, and return the elements that arise which match a pattern.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Then, we can ask the question: Given fib[3], what is the sequence of recursive Fibonacci calls?
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] In symbolic programming languages, it is easy to have patterns as arguments to functions or as elements of data structures.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] A consequence of this is the ability to use patterns to declaratively make statements about pieces of data and to flexibly instruct functions how to operate.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] For instance, the Mathematica function `Compile` can be used to make more efficient versions of the code.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] The Curry–Howard correspondence between proofs and programs relates ML-style pattern matching to case analysis and proof by exhaustion.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] By far the most common form of pattern matching involves strings of characters.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] In many programming languages, a particular syntax of strings is used to represent regular expressions, which are patterns describing string characters.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] However, it is possible to perform some string pattern matching within the same framework that has been discussed throughout this article.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] In Mathematica, strings are represented as trees of root StringExpression and all the characters in order as children of the root.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Thus, to match "any amount of trailing characters", a new wildcard ___ is needed in contrast to _ that would match only a single character.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] In Haskell and functional programming languages in general, strings are represented as functional lists of characters.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] A functional list is defined as an empty list, or an element constructed on an existing list.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] The structure for a list with some elements is thus `element:list`.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] When pattern matching, we assert that a certain piece of data is equal to a certain pattern.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] We assert that the first element of `head`'s argument is called element, and the function returns this.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] We know that this is the first element because of the way lists are defined, a single element constructed onto a list.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] The empty list would not match the pattern at all, as an empty list does not have a head (the first element that is constructed).
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] will match a string that has two characters and begins with "a".
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Symbolic entities can be introduced to represent many different classes of relevant features of a string.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] will match a string that consists of a letter first, and then a number.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] The main advantage of symbolic string manipulation is that it can be completely integrated with the rest of the programming language, rather than being a separate, special purpose subunit.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] The entire power of the language can be leveraged to build up the patterns themselves or analyze and transform the programs that contain them.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] SNOBOL (*StriNg Oriented and symBOlic Language*) is a computer programming language developed between 1962 and 1967 at AT&T Bell Laboratories by David J.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] SNOBOL4 stands apart from most programming languages by having patterns as a first-class data type (*i.e.* a data type whose values can be manipulated in all ways permitted to any other data type in the programming language) and by providing operators for pattern concatenation and alternation.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Strings generated during execution can be treated as programs and executed.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] SNOBOL was quite widely taught in larger US universities in the late 1960s and early 1970s and was widely used in the 1970s and 1980s as a text manipulation language in the humanities.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] Since SNOBOL's creation, newer languages such as AWK and Perl have made string manipulation by means of regular expressions fashionable.
[src:yara-rules/pattern-matching] SNOBOL4 patterns, however, subsume Backus–Naur form (BNF) grammars, which are equivalent to context-free grammars and more powerful than regular expressions.
[src:yara-rules/virustotal] It aggregates many antivirus products and online scan engines called Contributors.
[src:yara-rules/virustotal] In November, 2018, the Cyber National Mission Force, a unit subordinate to the U.S.
[src:yara-rules/virustotal] The aggregated data from these Contributors allows a user to check for viruses that the user's own antivirus software may have missed, or to verify against any false positives.
[src:yara-rules/virustotal] Files up to 650 MB can be uploaded to the website or up to 32 MB sent via email.
[src:yara-rules/virustotal] Antivirus software vendors can receive copies of files that were flagged by other scans but passed by their own engine, to help improve their software and, by extension, VirusTotal's own capability.
[src:yara-rules/virustotal] Users can also scan suspect URLs and search through the VirusTotal dataset.
[src:yara-rules/virustotal] VirusTotal uses the Cuckoo sandbox for dynamic analysis of malware.
[src:yara-rules/virustotal] VirusTotal was selected by *PC World* as one of the best 100 products of 2007.
[src:yara-rules/virustotal] On July 2023, VirusTotal issued an apology after one of its staff unintentionally exposed the private information belonging to 5,600 VirusTotal's customers, including the email addresses of US Cyber Command, FBI, and NSA employees.
[src:yara-rules/yara] It provides a rule-based approach to create descriptions of malware families based on regular expression, textual or binary patterns.
[src:yara-rules/yara] A description is essentially a YARA rule name, where these rules consist of sets of strings and a Boolean expression.
[src:yara-rules/yara] Analysts write YARA rules to capture the DNA of malware families, persistent elements like code fragments, configuration strings, and structural patterns expressed as text, hex sequences, or regex with Boolean logic.
[src:yara-rules/yara] This signature-based detection survives file mutations that defeat hash matching, enabling identification of variants and related samples across large datasets.
[src:yara-rules/yara] YARA was originally developed by Victor Alvarez of VirusTotal and released on GitHub in 2013.
[src:yara-rules/yara] The name is an abbreviation of *YARA: Another Recursive Acronym* or *Yet Another Ridiculous Acronym.* In 2024, Alvarez announced that YARA would be superseded by a rewrite called YARA-X, written in Rust.
[src:yara-rules/yara] A first stable version of YARA-X was released in June 2025, marking the passage of the original YARA into maintenance mode.
[src:yara-rules/yara] YARA by default comes with modules to process PE, ELF analysis, as well as support for the open-source Cuckoo sandbox.
